There is no official web-based version of VLC Media Player that runs entirely inside a browser tab without local software. However, you can achieve "online" functionalitpasted9:48 AMClaude responded: That's a genuinely tricky bottleneck, and the previous AI got most of it right.I notice the user prompt is empty, so I cannot determine the primary language or provide an appropriate summary. Please provide the user prompt so I can create an accurate summary in the correct languageI notice the user prompt is empty, so I cannot determine the primary language or provide an appropriate summary. Please provide the user prompt so I can create an accurate summary in the correct languageThat's a genuinely tricky bottleneck, and the previous AI got most of it right. Let me cut straight to the practical paths forward for your specific situation.
The core problem in one sentence: The IP-lock means only the user's browser can fetch the file, so you can't touch it server-side, and AC3 is unlicensed in browsers, so you can't play it natively.
Here's what actually works in the real world:

Option 1: Service Worker as a Local CORS Proxy (Clever Browser-Only Fix)
A Service Worker runs inside the user's browser, meaning it shares the user's IP. It can intercept the Debrid request, fetch it (IP-lock satisfied), and serve it back to your page with the right headers (CORS satisfied). This solves both problems in one shot — no external server needed.
For the AC3 audio, you'd pair this with ffmpeg.wasm running in a Web Worker to transcode only the audio track to AAC on the client. Transcoding just audio is far lighter than full video — much more practical than the full Wasm player approach.
Option 2: The Stremio/Koa Model (What Everyone Else Does)
Almost every successful Debrid-based service (Stremio, Syncler, Debrid Media Manager) doesn't fight the browser at all. They ship a small local companion app or use a protocol handler. Your website stays lightweight, and clicking "Play" fires off vlc://your-debrid-link or a custom yourapp:// URI that launches a local helper.
This is the lowest-effort path to a reliable product.
Option 3: Electron Desktop App
Wrap your web UI in Electron, bundle libmpv or ffmpeg, and you get native AC3 support plus the user's IP for Debrid links. This is how Stremio's desktop app actually works under the hood.

My honest recommendation:
If you want a web player, the Service Worker + ffmpeg.wasm audio-only transcode is the most technically sound path that keeps everything client-side. It's non-trivial but very doable.
If you want a shipped product fast, go with the "Open in VLC / external player" deep-link approach now, and build the native app later.
