You're probably thinking HLS vs one of these:

DASH (Dynamic Adaptive Streaming) — similar to HLS, also segment based
Progressive download — just a direct MP4 link, no segments
RTMP — old streaming protocol, basically dead for browsers

My guess is you're landing on HLS, and yes that's correct. Here's why it's the right call for your setup:
FFmpeg takes the Debrid link, transcodes the AC3 to AAC, and outputs an HLS stream which is just a .m3u8 playlist file pointing to small video chunks. Your browser player reads that .m3u8 file using HLS.js and plays it natively.
Debrid Link → FFmpeg → .m3u8 + .ts chunks → HLS.js → Your Browser Player
The advantages for your specific case:

Starts playing before the whole file downloads
Works on every browser with HLS.js
FFmpeg handles HLS output natively, no extra libraries
Adaptive bitrate if you want it later

