Multi-audio tracks:
When FFmpeg transcodes to HLS, mapping multiple language tracks cleanly into the stream is genuinely complicated. You have to explicitly map each track, label them, and HLS.js has to expose them to your player UI. What works perfectly in VLC out of the box becomes a significant engineering task.
Link reliability:
This is a serious operational problem. Client-side, if the link breaks, the user just gets a new one. Server-side you now need:

A health checking system constantly pinging links
Logic to detect when a link dies mid-stream
Automatic re-fetching from Debrid
A way to seamlessly swap the stream without interrupting the user

Request load on the provider:
Every health check, every re-fetch, every new stream start = another request to Debrid from your server. Debrid providers watch for this kind of pattern and can throttle or ban accounts that look like they're being shared or automated heavily.
So the honest summary is:
The server-side approach solves the browser playback problem but trades it for three new operational problems that are arguably harder to manage.
