That's genuinely it at the core. But let me break it down:
Why content comes in DTS/AC3/TrueHD instead of AAC:

Blu-ray disc standard literally mandates Dolby or DTS. AAC is not an allowed format on a Blu-ray disc. So every physical disc ever pressed has Dolby or DTS baked in.
When someone rips a Blu-ray they just copy what's already there. Nobody wants to re-encode and lose quality.
DTS-HD MA and TrueHD are lossless. AAC is lossy. For people who care about audio quality, converting lossless to lossy is unacceptable.

Why streaming services use EAC3 instead of AAC:

Dolby Digital Plus carries surround sound metadata that AAC simply doesn't handle as well
Dolby Atmos is built on top of EAC3. There is no AAC equivalent of Atmos.
Netflix, Disney+, Amazon all want to say "Dolby Atmos supported" on their marketing. That requires EAC3.

The cruel irony for you:
AAC actually sounds great and most people genuinely cannot tell the difference in a blind test. But the industry standardised on Dolby and DTS decades ago at the hardware level and nobody is changing that.
The browser is basically the only mainstream media platform in existence that never got the memo.You said: this is cult or monopolythis is cult or monopoly10:12 AMClaude responded: Both honestly.Both honestly.
The Dolby monopoly part:
Dolby has been the standard in cinema since the 1970s. They got into every cinema, every studio, every mixing room, every TV, every Blu-ray player. Once you're that deeply embedded into an entire industry's workflow, you don't need to compete anymore. Everyone just uses Dolby because everything else uses Dolby.
DTS came along and managed to carve out a share but even they eventually just coexisted rather than displaced Dolby. There was never real competition that drove prices down for developers and browser vendors.
The cult part:
Audiophiles and home theatre enthusiasts treat Dolby Atmos and DTS-HD MA like religion. Ask anyone in those communities if AAC is "good enough" and they will genuinely get angry at you. The perception of quality became more important than the measurable difference in quality. Most people on a normal TV with normal speakers cannot hear the difference between a good AAC encode and DTS-HD MA. But the culture around it is so strong that nobody in the content pipeline questions it.
The result for you:
An entire browser ecosystem of billions of devices can't play the dominant audio format because:

Dolby charges too much for browser licensing
The content industry won't switch away from Dolby
Audiophile culture keeps demand for lossless formats alive
Browser vendors won't pay

