Just for Chrome. Just for AC3 support.
And that's why Google said no.
The really infuriating part though:
Dolby only charges for one technology per device, meaning if a device already includes an existing Dolby technology, additional formats effectively cost nothing. Wikipedia
So Apple and Microsoft already pay Dolby for their operating systems. Adding browser support costs them basically nothing extra on top of what they already pay. That's why Safari and Edge support it but Chrome doesn't.
Google never paid Dolby at the OS level for Chrome OS or Android browser, so they'd have to pay fresh. And at 3 billion devices that number is simply too big.
