Show moreDoneKeep digging? Here's what else is out there:
The multiple audio tracks trick
Many MKV files from torrents already have a secondary AAC stereo track sitting right there alongside the DTS/AC3 surround track. People ignore it because media players default to the surround track. You could demux the file, detect if an AAC track exists, and serve just that to Chrome users with zero transcoding needed. Free. Instant. Works right now.
WebCodecs API
A newer browser API that gives JavaScript much lower level access to media decoding. It's not a magic fix for AC3 but it gives you much finer control over how you handle tracks and could pair well with the liba52.wasm approach to be more efficient than previous Wasm methods.
Codec detection + smart serving
Your player detects what the browser supports before starting playback. Safari gets the raw EAC3 stream directly. Chrome gets either the secondary AAC track if it exists, or triggers transcoding only as a last resort. You only pay the transcoding cost when you absolutely have to.
Opus transcoding
If you do end up transcoding, transcode to Opus instead of AAC. It's open, royalty free, better quality than AAC at lower bitrates, and Chrome/Firefox support it natively. Safari doesn't though, so you'd serve Opus to Chrome and AAC to Safari.
The biggest one honestly
Since EAC3 patents just expired in January, watch Firefox and Chrome bug trackers closely. Someone will submit a patch to enable native EAC3 support. When that lands your entire problem disappears overnight with zero code changes on your end.
